                            <comment id="17880642" author="janhoy" created="Tue, 10 Sep 2024 13:34:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It works, you just have to find the PID of the JAVA process running Solr.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Say you &quot;docker exec&quot; into the running solr container, then run &quot;ps -ef&quot;, you&apos;ll see the list of PIDs. On one of my containers it was PID 14. Then use that PID.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Closing. In the future, please ask questions like this on the users@solr.apache.org mailing list, not in JIRA.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17880652" author="rmueller83" created="Tue, 10 Sep 2024 13:50:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the response!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Maybe it is possible to improve the documentation here, since a lot of people are used to the default PID 1.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17880653" author="janhoy" created="Tue, 10 Sep 2024 13:52:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Sure, feel free to file a doc PR with a suggested change.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17881211" author="janhoy" created="Thu, 12 Sep 2024 08:22:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Reopen for better docs&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17881219" author="janhoy" created="Thu, 12 Sep 2024 08:33:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Note that a you CAN have Solr run as PID 1 by setting the environment variable &lt;tt&gt;TINI=no&lt;/tt&gt;. This is documented in the Docker page of the refguide too.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
